2182C - Production of Snowmen
A straightforward solution that checks all triples runs in $$$O(n^4)$$$, which is too slow. Let's try to speed it up.
We can improve the complexity to $$$O(n^3)$$$ by checking only $$$n^2$$$ triples instead of $$$n^3$$$ triples. We will only check triples where $$$j = 1$$$. How can we account for triples where $$$j \ne 1$$$ in the answer? In fact, each of those triples will already be considered with $$$j = 1$$$: the triple $$$(i, j, k)$$$ is equivalent to the triple $$$(i - (j - 1), 1, k - (j - 1))$$$ — using them will yield the same snowmen, just in a different order. This allows us to only consider triples where $$$j = 1$$$, and then multiply the answer by $$$n$$$.
Unfortunately, this is still too slow. To achieve an even faster solution, we can notice that in the combination $$$(i, j, k)$$$, the value of $$$i$$$ can conflict with the value of $$$j$$$ (if for some snowman with such values the head is not smaller than the body), the value of $$$j$$$ can conflict with the value of $$$k$$$ (if for some snowman with such values the body is not smaller than the legs), however, the values of $$$i$$$ and $$$k$$$ do not impose restrictions on each other. Therefore, instead of checking triples $$$(i, j, k)$$$, we can find the number of suitable values for $$$i$$$ and suitable values for $$$k$$$ for a given value of $$$j$$$, and then multiply these two numbers.
Thus, the solution consists of the following steps:
count how many values of $$$i$$$ are available for $$$j = 1$$$;
count how many values of $$$k$$$ are available for $$$j = 1$$$;
multiply these two numbers to get the number of suitable triples $$$(i, j, k)$$$ for $$$j = 1$$$;
multiply the answer by $$$n$$$ to account for the fact that the parameter $$$j$$$ does not necessarily have to be equal to $$$1$$$.
This solution already works in $$$O(n^2)$$$, which is fast enough given the problem constraints.
